#X text 161 129 By default we have a linear tracking in pitch difference. But you can use exponential factors. An exponential factor of '1' or '0' is linear and '0' is the default. Values greater than one expand the tracking amount \, where A semitone difference is much lower than higher intervals. Regardless of the exponential factor \, if you have a tracking amount of 100% \, an octave higher or lower will still be the same as linear (respectively '2' and '0.5'). Exponential values lower than 1 have the opposite behaviour. Note that below and above the reference point(s) we have a mirrored behaviour., f 74;
#X text 163 233 Hence \, they form a sort of 'S' shaped curve. The plot below is done with a [rescale] object., f 31;
#X obj 133 299 else/knob 61 0 200 0 100 empty empty #dfdfdf #7c7c7c #000000 1 0 0 0 1 320 0 0 0 empty empty 0 12 0 -15 0 1 0 0 0 0;
#X floatatom 133 378 8 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X text 217 310 Changing the amount also affects the overall range of the curve., f 26;
#X text 36 422 You can have negative values \, which will reverse the mapping. For instance \, with "-1" the ratio decreases above the the reference point(s). Test above., f 24;
