#X text 32 227 see also:;
#X text 51 86 [keytrack] maps MIDI pitch input from a keyboard and outputs a function you can use to control things like a filter cutoff. By default we have MIDI pitch 60 (middle C) as an unaltered reference point (ratio 1). Hence \, the mapping occurs above and down the reference point or range (as you can set a lower and upper reference points forming an unaltered range). The tracking amount affects the mapping amount \, where a minimum value of 0 sets no tracking (all ratios are equal to 1). See also [keytrack2] \, which lets you set different parameters up and down the reference range., f 79;
#X obj 32 247 else/keytrack~;
#X obj 32 267 else/keytrack2;
#X text 99 352 exp <float> -;
#X text 185 351 exponential factor;
#X text 135 391 float -;
#X text 185 391 track amount value;
#X text 149 477 -exp <float>: exponential factors (default 0 \, linear);
#X text 157 507 1) float - track amount (default 100);
#X text 157 524 2) list - up to 2 reference points (default 60);
